    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ in Reggaetón ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "S-reduction in coda is a very common phonological feature of reggaetón production. In online lyric transcripts, you will find people mark words with etymological /s/ with an ' (e.g., no me mire') to indicate an intentional reduction. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Alveolar Fricatives in Coda Articulation/Orthographic Representation  \nS-Reduction Coda /s/ in Puerto Rico S-Reduction in Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Below are examples that demonstrate claims made in research about the nature of /s/ reduction in reggaetón",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Listen Here ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The following examples are designed to showcase the findings of research on /s/ reduction in contemporary reggeatón. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ is seen as a genre-specific index of artistic affiliation. This means that scholars have found  artists reduce /s/ significantly more when performing reggaetón but not other genres. Below are examples of Puerto Rican artists specifically who showcase this pattern. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Ivy Queen "
        }
      ]
    },
